(154, 1, '2016-12-21 08:42:34', '2016-12-21 08:42:34', 'In this article, we have explained very latest jQuery trick and tips so that you can also implement in your code where needed. jQuery provides wonderful functions that executes within no time but the way of use depends on the programmer. Please see the following jquery trick and tips with examples:\r\n\r\n<strong>1. Count DOM elements of Your Web Page</strong>\r\nThere are many web sites that takes too long to load the page. A simple fact: the more content your page has, the more time it takes your browser to render it. You can get a quick count of the number of DOM(Document Object Model) elements on your page by running this in your console:\r\n\r\n[js]console.log( $(\'*\').length );[/js]\r\n\r\nThe smaller the number, the faster the website is rendered. If the number is bigger, you must try to optimize it if possible by removing redundant markup and unnecessary wrapping elements. There are many tricks like AJAX, only load necessary markup to make the main layout so that visitor can wait to load the other content.\r\n\r\n<strong>2. Keep your selectors very simple where possible</strong>\r\n\r\njQuery library provides us a very simple syntex to perform the operations on the DOM elements but it becomes developer\'s reponsibility to choose the best method to select any DOM element. You should try to optimize the way you retrieve elements. There are many users that use the older browsers that force jQuery into traversing the DOM tree, which is very slow.\r\n\r\n[js]\r\n$(\'li[data-selected=&quot;true&quot;] a\')	// Fancy, but very slow\r\n$(\'li.selected a\')	// Better\r\n$(\'#elem\')	// Best\r\n[/js]\r\n\r\nSelecting DOM element by its id is the fastest because Jquery directly jumps on that specific element without any traversing process. If you need to select by class name, prefix it with a tag – $(\'li.selected\'). These optimizations mainly affect older browsers and mobile devices.\r\n\r\nTo minimizing the accessing of the DOM elements, there is a best way to cache the results in the jQuery varible. Please see the following example:\r\n\r\n[js]\r\nvar buttons = $(\'#navigation a.button\');\r\n\r\n// Some prefer prefixing their jQuery variables with $:\r\nvar $buttons = $(\'#navigation a.button\');\r\n[/js]\r\n\r\nThe variable you choose will hold a jQuery object, which you can access later in your script where needed.\r\n\r\nAnother thing worth noting, is that jQuery gives you a large number of additional selectors for convenience, such as :visible, :hidden, :animated and more, which are not valid CSS3 selectors. The result is that if you use them the library cannot utilize querySelectorAll(). To remedy the situation, you can first select the elements you want to work with, and later filter them, like this:\r\n\r\n[js]\r\n$(\'a.button:animated\');	// Does not use querySelectorAll()\r\n$(\'a.button\').filter(\':animated\');	// Uses it\r\n[/js]\r\n\r\nThe results of the above are the same, with the exception that the second example is faster.\r\n\r\n<strong>3. Turn your jQuery Code into a Plugin</strong>\r\n\r\nIf you invest some time in writing a piece of jQuery code, consider turning it into a plugin. This promotes code reuse, limits dependencies and helps you organize your project\'s code base. Please see the following example to write the plugin in jQuery:\r\n\r\n[js]\r\n(function($){\r\n	$.fn.yourPluginName = function(){\r\n		// Your code goes here\r\n		return this;\r\n	};\r\n})(jQuery);\r\n[/js]\r\n\r\n<strong>4. Understand the difference between .on() and .click() function</strong>\r\n\r\nThe basic difference between .on() and .click() functions is in usage patterns. I would prefer .on() over .click() because the former can use less memory and work for dynamically added elements. Dynamically added elements means, the elements that are added after the DOM is ready, e.g. elements added by AJAX, by using .html() method etc.\r\n\r\nConsider the following html:\r\n\r\n[html]\r\n&lt;button id=&quot;add&quot;&gt;Add new&lt;/button&gt;\r\n\r\n&lt;div id=&quot;container&quot;&gt;\r\n        &lt;button class=&quot;alert&quot;&gt;alert!&lt;/button&gt;\r\n    &lt;/div&gt;\r\n\r\n[/html]\r\n\r\nand want \"Alert!\" to show an alert. We can use either \"click\" or \"on\" for that.\r\nWhen we use click\r\n\r\n[js]\r\n$(&quot;button.alert&quot;).click(function() {\r\n    alert(1);\r\n});\r\n[/js]\r\n\r\nwith the above, a separate handler gets created for every single element that matches the selector. That means:\r\na. many matching elements would create many identical handlers and thus increase memory footprint\r\nb. dynamically added items won\'t have the handler - ie, in the above html the newly added \"Alert!\" buttons won\'t work unless you rebind the handler.\r\n\r\nWhen we use .on\r\n\r\n[js]\r\n$(&quot;div#container&quot;).on(\'click\', \'button.alert\', function() {\r\n    alert(1);\r\n});\r\n[js]&lt;/pre&gt;\r\n\r\nwith the above, a single handler for all elements that match your selector, including the ones created dynamically.\r\n\r\n&lt;strong&gt;5. Passing named functions as event handlers&lt;/strong&gt;\r\n\r\nYou can also pass the function name in the callback. However, you can create a function ahead of time and store it in a variable, then pass that variable as the event handler. This is useful if you want to use the same handler for different events or events on different elements. Please see the following example:\r\n&lt;pre&gt;[js]\r\n var handleClick = function() {\r\n  console.log( \'something was clicked\' );\r\n};\r\n\r\n$( \'li\' ).on( \'click\', handleClick );\r\n$( \'h1\' ).on( \'click\', handleClick );\r\n[/js]\r\n', 'Latest jQuery Tricks and Tips', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'latest-jquery-tricks-and-tips', '', '', '2017-01-13 16:34:06', '2017-01-13 11:04:06', '', 0, 'http://trickntip.com/?p=154', 0, 'post', '', 2),
