hen it executes if\'s body otherwise if\'s body part will be skipped. Many time we do not need to check the conditions\nin \'if\' statement like existence checks. We often see stuff like this:\n[js]var a = [1, 2, 3, 4, 5];\n\nif (a.length &amp;gt; 0) {\n // do your stuff\n}\n[/js]\ninstead of above code, for example just do this:\n[js]var a = [1, 2, 3, 4, 5];\nif (a.length) { // if length is not equal to 0, this will be true\n // do your stuff\n}\n[/js]\nThere\'s all kinds of existence checks you can do, but this was just a simple example to illustrate a point\n\nPlease see the following example on how to use a default value:\n[js]function fun(anyArgument) {\n  anyArgument || (anyArgument = &quot;Fun With JavaScript is a great post&quot;);\n  alert(anyArgument); 	\n}\nfun(); //alert Fun With JavaScript is a great post\nfun(\'Fun With JavaScript\'); //alert Fun With JavaScript \n[/js]\n5. Converting variable to boolean using !!(Double negation operator) operator.\n\nMany times we need to check variable existence or if it has a valid value,\nSometimes we need to check if some variable exists or if it has a valid value, to consider them as true value. This sort of validations can be handled easily using !!(Double negation operator) which will automatically convert any type of data to boolean value. This variable will return false only if it has 0, null, \"\", undefined or NaN, otherwise it will return true\n\nTo understand it in practice, take a look this simple example:\n[js]function BankAccount(cash) {  \n    this.cash = cash;\n    this.hasMoney = !!cash;\n}\nvar bnkAcc = new BankAccount(10.5);  \nconsole.log(bnkAcc.cash); // 10.5  \nconsole.log(bnkAcc.hasMoney); // true\n\nvar emtyBnkAcc = new BankAccount(0);  \nconsole.log(emtyBnkAcc.cash); // 0  \nconsole.log(emtyBnkAcc.hasMoney); // false  \n[/js]\nIn this case, if an bnkAcc.cash value is greater than zero, the account.hasMoney will be true.\n\n6. JavaScript Short-circuits conditionals\n\nWe are all programmers and we choose the best code so that we can shorten the file size and execution. Please see the following code:\n[js] if (conected) {  \n   doLogin();\n }\n[/js]\nYou can make your code smaller by using the combination of a variable (which will be verified first) and a function using the &amp;&amp; (AND operator) between both. For example, the previous code can be written in one line:\n[]   conected &amp;&amp; doLogin();  \n</pre>\n<h2>Conclusion</h2>\nNow you learned some useful JavaScript tricks with \'Fun With JavaScript\' post which are largely used to shorten JavaScript code and some of these tricks are used in many popular JS frameworks. If you want to go more deeper and want to know how these tricks works implicitly then you can start playing with these and explore more JavaScript behaviors. We hope you enjoyed this post and if you know other JS hacks, please let us and keep sharing this post.\n\nThanks!', 'Fun With JavaScript', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '160-autosave-v1', '', '', '2017-01-10 13:23:13', '2017-01-10 07:53:13', '', 160, 'http://trickntip.com/160-autosave-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
