(190, 1, '2016-12-23 06:05:21', '2016-12-23 06:05:21', 'JavaScript is very popular scripting language which covers the major part of your website development. There are many tricks in that can be used to Fun With JavaScript.\r\n\r\nWhen we write the code, there are many hacks and breakdowns possible in the programming language that we are unaware about those. To just get rid of those breakdowns, we have written this Fun With JavaScript article.\r\n\r\n[caption id=\"attachment_188\" align=\"alignnone\" width=\"592\"]<img class=\" wp-image-188\" src=\"http://trickntip.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/12/Fun-With-JavaScript.jpeg\" alt=\"Fun With JavaScript\" width=\"592\" height=\"221\" /> Fun With JavaScript[/caption]\r\n\r\nYou can see the following examples and also try when you get a chance. We have tried to explain this in detail with the possible output in comments:\r\n\r\n1. Please see the output of \'==\' operator in the following code:\r\n<pre>alert(\'\' == \'0\'); //false\r\nalert(0 == \'\'); // true\r\nalert(0 ==\'0\'); // true\r\nalert(\'\\n\\t\\r \' == 0) // true\r\n</pre>\r\nTherefore, always use === and !== instead of == and !=\r\n\r\n2. Large loops are faster in while-condition and backwards - i.e., if the order of the loop doesn\'t matter to you.\r\nIn about 50% of our code, it usually doesn\'t.\r\ni.e.\r\n<pre>var i, len = 100000;\r\n\r\nfor (var i = 0; i &lt; len; i++) {\r\n  // do stuff\r\n}\r\n\r\nIs slower than:\r\n\r\ni = len;\r\nwhile (i--) {\r\n  // do stuff\r\n} \r\n\r\n</pre>\r\n3. You don\'t need to define any formal parameters for a function. There is an \'arguments\' array that you can just use inside the function like object.\r\n<pre>function sum() {\r\n    var retval = 0;\r\n    for (var i = 0, len = arguments.length; i &lt; len; ++i) {\r\n        retval += arguments[i];\r\n    }\r\n    return retval;\r\n}\r\n\r\nsum(1, 2, 3, 4) // returns 10\r\n</pre>\r\n4. Understand \'if\' statement so that you can speed up execution time of your code. We all know that \'if\' statement works on boolean, if your\r\ncondition returns \'true\' then it executes if\'s body otherwise if\'s body part will be skipped. Many time we do not need to check the conditions\r\nin \'if\' statement like existence checks. We often see stuff like this:\r\n<pre>var a = [1, 2, 3, 4, 5];\r\n\r\nif (a.length &gt; 0) {\r\n // do your stuff\r\n}\r\n</pre>\r\ninstead of above code, for example just do this:\r\n<pre>var a = [1, 2, 3, 4, 5];\r\nif (a.length) { // if length is not equal to 0, this will be true\r\n // do your stuff\r\n}\r\n</pre>\r\nThere\'s all kinds of existence checks you can do, but this was just a simple example to illustrate a point\r\n\r\nPlease see the following example on how to use a default value:\r\n<pre>function fun(anyArgument) {\r\n  anyArgument || (anyArgument = \"Fun With JavaScript is a great post\");\r\n  alert(anyArgument); 	\r\n}\r\nfun(); //alert Fun With JavaScript is a great post\r\nfun(\'Fun With JavaScript\'); //alert Fun With JavaScript \r\n</pre>', 'Fun With JavaScript', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '160-revision-v1', '', '', '2016-12-23 06:05:21', '2016-12-23 06:05:21', '', 160, 'http://trickntip.com/160-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
