(193, 1, '2016-12-23 06:44:34', '2016-12-23 06:44:34', 'JavaScript is very popular scripting language which covers the major part of your website development. There are many tricks in that can be used to Fun With JavaScript.\r\n\r\nWhen we write the code, there are many hacks and breakdowns possible in the programming language that we are unaware about those. To just get rid of those breakdowns, we have written this Fun With JavaScript article.\r\n\r\n[caption id=\"attachment_188\" align=\"alignnone\" width=\"592\"]<img class=\" wp-image-188\" src=\"http://trickntip.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/12/Fun-With-JavaScript.jpeg\" alt=\"Fun With JavaScript\" width=\"592\" height=\"221\" /> Fun With JavaScript[/caption]\r\n\r\nYou can see the following examples and also try when you get a chance. We have tried to explain this in detail with the possible output in comments:\r\n\r\n1. Please see the output of \'==\' operator in the following code:\r\n<pre>alert(\'\' == \'0\'); //false\r\nalert(0 == \'\'); // true\r\nalert(0 ==\'0\'); // true\r\nalert(\'\\n\\t\\r \' == 0) // true\r\n</pre>\r\nTherefore, always use === and !== instead of == and !=\r\n\r\n2. Large loops are faster in while-condition and backwards - i.e., if the order of the loop doesn\'t matter to you.\r\nIn about 50% of our code, it usually doesn\'t.\r\ni.e.\r\n<pre>var i, len = 100000;\r\n\r\nfor (var i = 0; i &lt; len; i++) {\r\n  // do stuff\r\n}\r\n\r\nIs slower than:\r\n\r\ni = len;\r\nwhile (i--) {\r\n  // do stuff\r\n} \r\n\r\n</pre>\r\n3. You don\'t need to define any formal parameters for a function. There is an \'arguments\' array that you can just use inside the function like object.\r\n<pre>function sum() {\r\n    var retval = 0;\r\n    for (var i = 0, len = arguments.length; i &lt; len; ++i) {\r\n        retval += arguments[i];\r\n    }\r\n    return retval;\r\n}\r\n\r\nsum(1, 2, 3, 4) // returns 10\r\n</pre>\r\n4. Understand \'if\' statement so that you can speed up execution time of your code. We all know that \'if\' statement works on boolean, if your\r\ncondition returns \'true\' then it executes if\'s body otherwise if\'s body part will be skipped. Many time we do not need to check the conditions\r\nin \'if\' statement like existence checks. We often see stuff like this:\r\n<pre>var a = [1, 2, 3, 4, 5];\r\n\r\nif (a.length &gt; 0) {\r\n // do your stuff\r\n}\r\n</pre>\r\ninstead of above code, for example just do this:\r\n<pre>var a = [1, 2, 3, 4, 5];\r\nif (a.length) { // if length is not equal to 0, this will be true\r\n // do your stuff\r\n}\r\n</pre>\r\nThere\'s all kinds of existence checks you can do, but this was just a simple example to illustrate a point\r\n\r\nPlease see the following example on how to use a default value:\r\n<pre>function fun(anyArgument) {\r\n  anyArgument || (anyArgument = \"Fun With JavaScript is a great post\");\r\n  alert(anyArgument); 	\r\n}\r\nfun(); //alert Fun With JavaScript is a great post\r\nfun(\'Fun With JavaScript\'); //alert Fun With JavaScript \r\n</pre>\r\n5. Converting variable to boolean using !!(Double negation operator) operator.\r\n\r\nMany times we need to check variable existence or if it has a valid value,\r\nSometimes we need to check if some variable exists or if it has a valid value, to consider them as true value. This sort of validations can be handled easily using !!(Double negation operator) which will automatically convert any type of data to boolean value. This variable will return false only if it has 0, null, \"\", undefined or NaN, otherwise it will return true\r\n\r\nTo understand it in practice, take a look this simple example:\r\n<pre>function BankAccount(cash) {  \r\n    this.cash = cash;\r\n    this.hasMoney = !!cash;\r\n}\r\nvar bnkAcc = new BankAccount(10.5);  \r\nconsole.log(bnkAcc.cash); // 10.5  \r\nconsole.log(bnkAcc.hasMoney); // true\r\n\r\nvar emtyBnkAcc = new BankAccount(0);  \r\nconsole.log(emtyBnkAcc.cash); // 0  \r\nconsole.log(emtyBnkAcc.hasMoney); // false  \r\n</pre>\r\nIn this case, if an bnkAcc.cash value is greater than zero, the account.hasMoney will be true.\r\n\r\n6. JavaScript Short-circuits conditionals\r\n\r\nWe are all programmers and we choose the best code so that we can shorten the file size and execution. Please see the following code:\r\n<pre> if (conected) {  \r\n   doLogin();\r\n }\r\n</pre>\r\nYou can make your code smaller by using the combination of a variable (which will be verified first) and a function using the &amp;&amp; (AND operator) between both. For example, the previous code can be written in one line:\r\n<pre>   conected &amp;&amp; doLogin();  \r\n</pre>\r\n<h2>Conclusion</h2>\r\nNow you learned some useful JavaScript tricks with \'Fun With JavaScript\' post which are largely used to shorten JavaScript code and some of these tricks are used in many popular JS frameworks. If you want to go more deeper and want to know how these tricks works implicitly then you can start playing with these and explore more JavaScript behaviors. We hope you enjoyed this post and if you know other JS hacks, please let us and keep sharing this post.\r\n\r\nThanks!', 'Fun With JavaScript', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '160-revision-v1', '', '', '2016-12-23 06:44:34', '2016-12-23 06:44:34', '', 160, 'http://trickntip.com/160-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(194, 1, '2016-12-23 16:20:58', '2016-12-23 16:20:58', '<h2>Introduction</h2>\nMostly, all programming languages like PHP, Java, Python etc support Object Oriented Programming features. JavaScript is a scripting language that can be used at client end. In this post we will learn that how we can define class in JavaScript and how we can access its properties in the same way as we do in other pure OOPs programming languages.\n\nOne important thing that you need to consider is that, there is no \'class\' keyword to define class in JavaScript. So question arise here that if there is no \'class\' keyword introduced by JavaScript writers then how we can define class in JavaScript. We will show you with the working examples in this post.\n\nThere are mainly three ways to define class in Javascript:\n<h3>1. Using a function</h3>\nThis is the most common way to define class in JavaScript. You just need to define a normal JavaScript function and use the \'new\' keyword to create an object so that you can access its properties. To define properties and methods for an object created using function(), you use the this keyword, as seen in the following example:\n<pre>function Student(name) {\n    this.name = name;\n    this.age = \"22\";\n    this.class = \"10th\";\n    this.getInfo = getStudentInfo;\n}\n \nfunction getStudentInfo() {\n    return this.name + \' \' + this.age + \' \' + this.class;\n}\n</pre>\nNow you need to instantiate an object using the \'Student\' class constructor function, set some properties and call methods you can do the following:\n<pre>var student = new Student(\'John\');\nstudent.class = \"12th\";\nalert(student.getInfo()); //John 22 12th\n</pre>\nAs you have seen that we have defined the method \'getStudentInfo\' outside of the class. There are other ways to define the method:\n<h3>1.1.Define methods inside the class</h3>\nIn the example before you have seen that the method getInfo() of the \'Student\' class was defined in a other function called getStudentInfo(). No doubt it will work fine but it has one drawback. The function defined outside of the class will remains in the \'global namespace\'. This means you may have naming conflicts with other classes or libraries. The way to prevent pollution of the global namespace, you can define your methods within the constructor function, like this:\n<pre>function Student(name) {\n    this.name = name;\n    this.age = \"22\";\n    this.class = \"10th\";\n    this.getInfo = function() {\n    	return this.name + \' \' + this.age + \' \' + this.class;\n    };\n}\n</pre>\nNow you just need to call the \'getInfo\' function with the \'student\' object.\n<h3>1.2. Add methods to prototype</h3>\nOur previous point has also a drawback. The method getInfo() is recreated every time you create a new object of class. There is another inexpensive way to overcome this drawback. You can add getInfo() to the prototype of the constructor function.\n<pre>function Student(name) {\n    this.name = name;\n    this.age = \"22\";\n    this.class = \"10th\";\n}\n \nStudent.prototype.getInfo = function() {\n    return this.name + \' \' + this.age + \' \' + this.class;\n};\n</pre>\nAgain, you can use the new objects exactly the same way as in above methods.\n<h2>2.Using Object Literals</h2>\nLiterals are shorter way to define objects and arrays in JavaScript. There are many ways to do this. Please see the follwing examples:\n<pre>var o = {};\ninstead of the \"normal\" way:\nvar o = new Object();\n\nFor arrays you can do:\nvar a = [];\ninstead of:\nvar a = new Array();\n</pre>\nSo, to be more professional, you can skip the class-like stuff and create an instance (object) immediately. Here\'s the same functionality as described in the previous examples, but using object literal syntax this time:\n<pre>var student = {\n    name: \'John\',\n    age: \"22\",\n    class: \"10th\",\n    getInfo: function() {\n    	return this.name + \' \' + this.age + \' \' + this.class;\n    }\n}\n</pre>\nIn this case you don\'t need to (and cannot) create an instance of the class, it already exists. So you simply start using this instance.\n\nstudent.age = \"24\";\nalert(student.getInfo());\n<h2>3. Singleton using a function</h2>\nThe third way to define class in JavaScript is a combination of the other two that you already saw. You can use a \'function\' and \'new\' keyword to define a singleton object. Please see the syntex:\n<pre>var student = new function(){\n    name: \'John\',\n    age: \"22\",\n    class: \"10th\",\n    getInfo: function() {\n    	return this.name + \' \' + this.age + \' \' + this.class;\n    }\n}\n</pre>\n<pre>student.age = \"24\";\nalert(student.getInfo());\n</pre>\nThe main difference in this method is, here we are using the new function(){...} which does two things at the same time: define a function (an anonymous constructor function) and invoke it with new.\n\nIts a bit confusing but its an option to define class in JavaScript.\n<h2>Summary</h2>\nSo you learn three different method', 'Define class in JavaScript', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '45-autosave-v1', '', '', '2016-12-23 16:20:58', '2016-12-23 16:20:58', '', 45, 'http://trickntip.com/45-autosave-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(195, 1, '2016-12-23 14:58:23', '2016-12-23 14:58:23', 'There are many possible cases when you need to work with the classes in javascript. There are many languages like PHP, Ruby, Java etc which provides these features. But you can also define classes and create objects in javascript too. Please see the following working example:\r\n<pre>function Calculate(){\r\n\r\n   this.add = function(a,b){\r\n     return a+b;\r\n   }\r\n\r\n   this.sub = function(a,b){\r\n     return a-b;\r\n   }\r\n\r\n}\r\nvar c = new Calculate(); //here I have created an object of Calculate\r\nalert(c.add(10,20)); //Simply call the function in alert\r\n</pre>\r\nIn this example, I have just created \'Calculate\' class with the function keyword. There are two functions in the class named \'add\' and \'sub\' which can be called after creating an object of \'Calculate\' class.', 'Define class in JavaScript', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '45-revision-v1', '', '', '2016-12-23 14:58:23', '2016-12-23 14:58:23', '', 45, 'http://trickntip.com/45-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
