\' class was defined in a other function called getStudentInfo(). No doubt it will work fine but it has one drawback. The function defined outside of the class will remains in the \'global namespace\'. This means you may have naming conflicts with other classes or libraries. The way to prevent pollution of the global namespace, you can define your methods within the constructor function, like this:\r\n<pre>function Student(name) {\r\n    this.name = name;\r\n    this.age = \"22\";\r\n    this.class = \"10th\";\r\n    this.getInfo = function() {\r\n    	return this.name + \' \' + this.age + \' \' + this.class;\r\n    };\r\n}\r\n</pre>\r\nNow you just need to call the \'getInfo\' function with the \'student\' object.\r\n<h3>1.2. Add methods to prototype</h3>\r\nOur previous point has also a drawback. The method getInfo() is recreated every time you create a new object of class. There is another inexpensive way to overcome this drawback. You can add getInfo() to the prototype of the constructor function.\r\n<pre>function Student(name) {\r\n    this.name = name;\r\n    this.age = \"22\";\r\n    this.class = \"10th\";\r\n}\r\n \r\nStudent.prototype.getInfo = function() {\r\n    return this.name + \' \' + this.age + \' \' + this.class;\r\n};\r\n</pre>\r\nAgain, you can use the new objects exactly the same way as in above methods.\r\n<h2>2.Using Object Literals</h2>\r\nLiterals are shorter way to define objects and arrays in JavaScript. There are many ways to do this. Please see the follwing examples:\r\n<pre>var o = {};\r\ninstead of the \"normal\" way:\r\nvar o = new Object();\r\n\r\nFor arrays you can do:\r\nvar a = [];\r\ninstead of:\r\nvar a = new Array();\r\n</pre>\r\nSo, to be more professional, you can skip the class-like stuff and create an instance (object) immediately. Here\'s the same functionality as described in the previous examples, but using object literal syntax this time:\r\n<pre>var student = {\r\n    name: \'John\',\r\n    age: \"22\",\r\n    class: \"10th\",\r\n    getInfo: function() {\r\n    	return this.name + \' \' + this.age + \' \' + this.class;\r\n    }\r\n}\r\n</pre>\r\nIn this case you don\'t need to (and cannot) create an instance of the class, it already exists. So you simply start using this instance.\r\n\r\nstudent.age = \"24\";\r\nalert(student.getInfo());\r\n<h2>3. Singleton using a function</h2>\r\n&nbsp;\r\nThe third way to define class in JavaScript is a combination of the other two that you already saw. You can use a \'function\' and \'new\' keyword to define a singleton object. Please see the syntex:\r\n<pre>\r\nvar student = new function(){\r\n    name: \'John\',\r\n    age: \"22\",\r\n    class: \"10th\",\r\n    getInfo: function() {\r\n    	return this.name + \' \' + this.age + \' \' + this.class;\r\n    }\r\n}\r\n</pre>\r\n<pre>\r\nstudent.age = \"24\";\r\nalert(student.getInfo());\r\n</pre>\r\nThe main difference in this method is, here we are using the new function(){...} which does two things at the same time: define a function (an anonymous constructor function) and invoke it with new. \r\n\r\nIts a bit confusing but its an option to define class in JavaScript.', 'Define class in JavaScript', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '45-revision-v1', '', '', '2016-12-23 16:15:41', '2016-12-23 16:15:41', '', 45, 'http://trickntip.com/45-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
