(244, 1, '2017-01-13 16:40:25', '2017-01-13 11:10:25', 'Before we understand call by value and call by address, its very important to understand the Actual arguments and Formal arguments.\r\n\r\n<strong>Actual Arguments: </strong>The parameter\'s value that we passed while calling the function is called Actual Arguments.\r\n\r\n<strong>Formal Arguments: </strong>The arguments list of parameters that we specify while declaring a function, are known as formal parameters.\r\n\r\n<strong>For Example:</strong>\r\n\r\n[c]int multiply(int a, int b)\r\n{\r\n     int c = a * b;\r\n     return c;\r\n}\r\n\r\nmain(\r\n{\r\n    int v1 =10;\r\n    int v2 = 20;\r\n    int v3 = multiply(v1, v2);\r\n    printf(&quot;%d&quot;, v3);\r\n}[/c]\r\n\r\nIn above example a and b are formal arguments where v1 and v2 are actual arguments.\r\n<h3>Call By Value</h3>\r\nActual arguments are copied to the formal arguments in the case of call by value, hence any operation performed by function on arguments does not affect actual parameters because we simply call the function just passing the values. It may be little confusing but let me explain this with the help of an example –\r\n<pre class=\"prettyprint prettyprinted\"><span class=\"kwd\">int</span><span class=\"pln\"> increment</span><span class=\"pun\">(</span><span class=\"kwd\">int</span> a<span class=\"pun\">)</span>\r\n<span class=\"pun\">{</span>\r\n    a <span class=\"pun\">=</span> <span class=\"kwd\">a</span><span class=\"pun\">+</span><span class=\"lit\">1</span><span class=\"pun\">;</span>\r\n    <span class=\"kwd\">return</span> <span class=\"kwd\">a</span><span class=\"pun\">;</span>\r\n<span class=\"pun\">}</span>\r\n\r\n<span class=\"pln\">main</span><span class=\"pun\">()</span>\r\n<span class=\"pun\">{</span>\r\n   <span class=\"kwd\">int</span><span class=\"pln\"> num1</span><span class=\"pun\">=4</span><span class=\"lit\">0</span><span class=\"pun\">;</span>\r\n   <span class=\"kwd\">int</span><span class=\"pln\"> num2 </span><span class=\"pun\">=</span><span class=\"pln\"> increment</span><span class=\"pun\">(</span><span class=\"pln\">num1</span><span class=\"pun\">);</span><span class=\"pln\">\r\n   printf</span><span class=\"pun\">(</span><span class=\"str\">\"num1 value is: %d\"</span><span class=\"pun\">,</span><span class=\"pln\"> num1</span><span class=\"pun\">);//output: num1 value is:40</span><span class=\"pln\">\r\n   printf</span><span class=\"pun\">(</span><span class=\"str\">\"num2 value is: %d\"</span><span class=\"pun\">,</span><span class=\"pln\"> num2</span><span class=\"pun\">);//output: num2 value is:41</span>\r\n<span class=\"pun\">}</span></pre>\r\n<h3>Call By Address</h3>\r\nIn call by address, address of memory location is passed instead of value. The formal arguments in this case are <a href=\"http://trickntip.com/pointer-variables-in-c/\">pointer</a> variables. Lets take an example of call by address:\r\n<pre class=\"prettyprint prettyprinted\"><span class=\"kwd\">void</span><span class=\"pln\"> increment</span><span class=\"pun\">(</span><span class=\"kwd\">int</span> *a<span class=\"pun\">)</span>\r\n<span class=\"pun\">{</span>\r\n    *a <span class=\"pun\">=</span> *<span class=\"kwd\">a </span><span class=\"pun\">+ </span><span class=\"lit\">1</span><span class=\"pun\">;</span>\r\n<span class=\"pun\">}</span>\r\n\r\n<span class=\"pln\">main</span><span class=\"pun\">()</span>\r\n<span class=\"pun\">{</span>\r\n   <span class=\"kwd\">int</span><span class=\"pln\"> num1</span><span class=\"pun\">=4</span><span class=\"lit\">0</span><span class=\"pun\">;</span>\r\n<span class=\"pln\">   increment</span><span class=\"pun\">(&amp;</span><span class=\"pln\">num1</span><span class=\"pun\">);</span><span class=\"pln\">\r\n   printf</span><span class=\"pun\">(</span><span class=\"str\">\"num1 value is: %d\"</span><span class=\"pun\">,</span><span class=\"pln\"> num1</span><span class=\"pun\">);//output: num1 value is:41</span>\r\n<span class=\"pun\">}</span></pre>\r\nThe difference is very simple, in call by address we have passed the address of the variable using address(&amp;) operator. In increment() function *a points to the address of num1 variable. When, the value of pointers are changed, the value in the pointed memory location also changes correspondingly.', 'Call By Value and Call By Address in C', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '79-revision-v1', '', '', '2017-01-13 16:40:25', '2017-01-13 11:10:25', '', 79, 'http://trickntip.com/79-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(245, 1, '2017-01-13 16:41:26', '2017-01-13 11:11:26', 'Before we understand call by value and call by address, its very important to understand the Actual arguments and Formal arguments.\r\n\r\n<strong>Actual Arguments: </strong>The parameter\'s value that we passed while calling the function is called Actual Arguments.\r\n\r\n<strong>Formal Arguments: </strong>The arguments list of parameters that we specify while declaring a function, are known as formal parameters.\r\n\r\n<strong>For Example:</strong>\r\n\r\n[c]int multiply(int a, int b)\r\n{\r\n     int c = a * b;\r\n     return c;\r\n}\r\n\r\nmain(\r\n{\r\n    int v1 =10;\r\n    int v2 = 20;\r\n    int v3 = multiply(v1, v2);\r\n    printf(&quot;%d&quot;, v3);\r\n}[/c]\r\n\r\nIn above example a and b are formal arguments where v1 and v2 are actual arguments.\r\n<h3>Call By Value</h3>\r\nActual arguments are copied to the formal arguments in the case of call by value, hence any operation performed by function on arguments does not affect actual parameters because we simply call the function just passing the values. It may be little confusing but let me explain this with the help of an example –\r\n<pre class=\"prettyprint prettyprinted\"><span class=\"kwd\">\r\n[c]int&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;pln&quot;&gt; increment&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;pun&quot;&gt;(&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;kwd&quot;&gt;int&lt;/span&gt; a&lt;span class=&quot;pun&quot;&gt;)&lt;/span&gt;\r\n&lt;span class=&quot;pun&quot;&gt;{&lt;/span&gt;\r\n    a &lt;span class=&quot;pun&quot;&gt;=&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class=&quot;kwd&quot;&gt;a&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;pun&quot;&gt;+&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;lit&quot;&gt;1&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;pun&quot;&gt;;&lt;/span&gt;\r\n    &lt;span class=&quot;kwd&quot;&gt;return&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class=&quot;kwd&quot;&gt;a&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;pun&quot;&gt;;&lt;/span&gt;\r\n&lt;span class=&quot;pun&quot;&gt;}&lt;/span&gt;\r\n\r\n&lt;span class=&quot;pln&quot;&gt;main&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;pun&quot;&gt;()&lt;/span&gt;\r\n&lt;span class=&quot;pun&quot;&gt;{&lt;/span&gt;\r\n   &lt;span class=&quot;kwd&quot;&gt;int&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;pln&quot;&gt; num1&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;pun&quot;&gt;=4&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;lit&quot;&gt;0&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;pun&quot;&gt;;&lt;/span&gt;\r\n   &lt;span class=&quot;kwd&quot;&gt;int&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;pln&quot;&gt; num2 &lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;pun&quot;&gt;=&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;pln&quot;&gt; increment&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;pun&quot;&gt;(&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;pln&quot;&gt;num1&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;pun&quot;&gt;);&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;pln&quot;&gt;\r\n   printf&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;pun&quot;&gt;(&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;str&quot;&gt;&quot;num1 value is: %d&quot;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;pun&quot;&gt;,&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;pln&quot;&gt; num1&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;pun&quot;&gt;);//output: num1 value is:40&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;pln&quot;&gt;\r\n   printf&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;pun&quot;&gt;(&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;str&quot;&gt;&quot;num2 value is: %d&quot;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;pun&quot;&gt;,&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;pln&quot;&gt; num2&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;pun&quot;&gt;);//output: num2 value is:41&lt;/span&gt;\r\n&lt;span class=&quot;pun&quot;&gt;}[/c]\r\n</span></pre>\r\n<h3>Call By Address</h3>\r\nIn call by address, address of memory location is passed instead of value. The formal arguments in this case are <a href=\"http://trickntip.com/pointer-variables-in-c/\">pointer</a> variables. Lets take an example of call by address:\r\n<pre class=\"prettyprint prettyprinted\"><span class=\"kwd\">\r\n[c]void&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;pln&quot;&gt; increment&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;pun&quot;&gt;(&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;kwd&quot;&gt;int&lt;/span&gt; *a&lt;span class=&quot;pun&quot;&gt;)&lt;/span&gt;\r\n&lt;span class=&quot;pun&quot;&gt;{&lt;/span&gt;\r\n    *a &lt;span class=&quot;pun&quot;&gt;=&lt;/span&gt; *&lt;span class=&quot;kwd&quot;&gt;a &lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;pun&quot;&gt;+ &lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;lit&quot;&gt;1&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;pun&quot;&gt;;&lt;/span&gt;\r\n&lt;span class=&quot;pun&quot;&gt;}&lt;/span&gt;\r\n\r\n&lt;span class=&quot;pln&quot;&gt;main&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;pun&quot;&gt;()&lt;/span&gt;\r\n&lt;span class=&quot;pun&quot;&gt;{&lt;/span&gt;\r\n   &lt;span class=&quot;kwd&quot;&gt;int&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;pln&quot;&gt; num1&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;pun&quot;&gt;=4&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;lit&quot;&gt;0&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;pun&quot;&gt;;&lt;/span&gt;\r\n&lt;span class=&quot;pln&quot;&gt;   increment&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;pun&quot;&gt;(&amp;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;pln&quot;&gt;num1&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;pun&quot;&gt;);&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;pln&quot;&gt;\r\n   printf&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;pun&quot;&gt;(&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;str&quot;&gt;&quot;num1 value is: %d&quot;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;pun&quot;&gt;,&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;pln&quot;&gt; num1&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;pun&quot;&gt;);//output: num1 value is:41&lt;/span&gt;\r\n&lt;span class=&quot;pun&quot;&gt;}[/c]\r\n</span></pre>\r\nThe difference is very simple, in call by address we have passed the address of the variable using address(&amp;) operator. In increment() function *a points to the address of num1 variable. When, the value of pointers are changed, the value in the pointed memory location also changes correspondingly.', 'Call By Value and Call By Address in C', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '79-revision-v1', '', '', '2017-01-13 16:41:26', '2017-01-13 11:11:26', '', 79, 'http://trickntip.com/79-revision-v