(248, 1, '2017-01-13 16:49:14', '2017-01-13 11:19:14', 'Before we understand call by value and call by address, its very important to understand the Actual arguments and Formal arguments.\r\n\r\n<strong>Actual Arguments: </strong>The parameter\'s value that we passed while calling the function is called Actual Arguments.\r\n\r\n<strong>Formal Arguments: </strong>The arguments list of parameters that we specify while declaring a function, are known as formal parameters.\r\n\r\n<strong>For Example:</strong>\r\n\r\n[c]int multiply(int a, int b)\r\n{\r\n     int c = a * b;\r\n     return c;\r\n}\r\n\r\nmain(\r\n{\r\n    int v1 =10;\r\n    int v2 = 20;\r\n    int v3 = multiply(v1, v2);\r\n    printf(&quot;%d&quot;, v3);\r\n}[/c]\r\n\r\nIn above example a and b are formal arguments where v1 and v2 are actual arguments.\r\n<h3>Call By Value</h3>\r\nActual arguments are copied to the formal arguments in the case of call by value, hence any operation performed by function on arguments does not affect actual parameters because we simply call the function just passing the values. It may be little confusing but let me explain this with the help of an example –\r\n\r\n[c]\r\nint increment(int a)\r\n{\r\n    a = a+1;\r\n    return a;\r\n}\r\n\r\nmain()\r\n{\r\n   int num1=40;\r\n   int num2 = increment(num1);\r\n   printf(&quot;num1 value is: %d&quot;, num1);//output: num1 value is:40\r\n   printf(&quot;num2 value is: %d&quot;, num2);//output: num2 value is:41\r\n}\r\n[/c]\r\n\r\n<h3>Call By Address</h3>\r\nIn call by address, address of memory location is passed instead of value. The formal arguments in this case are <a href=\"http://trickntip.com/pointer-variables-in-c/\">pointer</a> variables. Lets take an example of call by address:\r\n\r\n[c]\r\nvoid increment(int *a)\r\n{\r\n    *a = *a + 1;\r\n}\r\n\r\nmain()\r\n{\r\n   int num1=40;\r\n   increment(&amp;num1);\r\n   printf(&quot;num1 value is: %d&quot;, num1);//output: num1 value is:41\r\n}\r\n[/c]\r\n\r\nThe difference is very simple, in call by address we have passed the address of the variable using address(&amp;) operator. In increment() function *a points to the address of num1 variable. When, the value of pointers are changed, the value in the pointed memory location also changes correspondingly.', 'Call By Value and Call By Address in C', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '79-revision-v1', '', '', '2017-01-13 16:49:14', '2017-01-13 11:19:14', '', 79, 'http://trickntip.com/79-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(249, 1, '2017-01-13 17:28:58', '2017-01-13 11:58:58', 'Finally PHP 7 has been released with new features and improvements. New PHP 7 features are outstanding and enough to compete with strictly typed languages. The later versions of PHP are not that bad but PHP 7 features make PHP more robust. In this post we have explained the new PHP 7 features and improvements, you will see what\'s new in PHP 7:\r\n<h2>1. Scalar Type Declaration/Hints</h2>\r\nTo understand this, you must know the meaning of type declaration or type hints. We all are very familiar with actual and formal arguments. But here we are talking about the type(Data Type) of actual and formal arguments. You can specify the type hint in the function definition. This feature works in two flavors: coercive (default) and strict mode. The following example will make it more clear to you:\r\n\r\n[php]\r\n/**\r\n* Scalar type declarations/hints\r\n*/\r\n//declare(strict_types=1);\r\nfunction multiply(int $a, int $b) {\r\nreturn $a * $b;\r\n}\r\nvar_dump(add(2,4));\r\nvar_dump(add(&quot;2&quot;,&quot;4&quot;));\r\n\r\n[/php]\r\n\r\nThe coercive mode is enabled by default. This restricts PHP from throwing a type error when the types don\'t exactly match, but when a conversion is still possible. This feature ensures the better input consistency of methods.\r\n<h2>2. Return Type Declaration/Hints</h2>\r\nWe are very glad for this feature. Whereas the above PHP 7 feature ensures input consistency, return type declarations ensure output consistency.\r\n\r\n[php]\r\n\r\n/**\r\n* Return type declarations\r\n*/\r\n//declare(strict_types=1);\r\nfunction multiply(int $a, int $b): int{\r\nreturn (string)($a * $b);\r\n}\r\nvar_dump(multiply(4,2));\r\n\r\n[/php]\r\n\r\nHere, if you enable \"strict mode\" then this code will throw a type error because we have declared return type int but returning the string.\r\n<h2>3. Anonymous Classes</h2>\r\nAs JavaScript provide the feature of anonymous classes, PHP 7 has also introduced this feature. Using anonymous classes you can define a class and instantiate on object inline.\r\n\r\n[php]\r\n/**\r\n* Anonymous classes\r\n*/\r\n$obj= new class {\r\npublic function greetings() {\r\nreturn \'Good morning, Tricky Admin!\';\r\n}\r\n};\r\nvar_dump($obj,$obj-&gt;greetings());[/php]\r\n\r\n<h2>4. The Closure::call() Function</h2>\r\nThis function is more faster then the formal way. Actually, this is a shorthand way to bind a object scope to a closure and call it. Closure are anonymous functions that re declared inline and assigned to a variable. Its possible in PHP 5 but call method is just introduced to simplify the process.\r\n\r\n[php]/**\r\n* Closure::call()\r\n*/\r\nclass Greeting\r\n{\r\nprivate $morning = \'Good morning, Tricky Admin!\'.PHP_EOL;\r\n}\r\n$getGreetingCallback = function() {\r\nreturn $this-&gt;morning;\r\n};\r\n//Old PHP 5 style\r\n$binding = $getGreetingCallback-&gt;bindTo(new Greeting,\'Greeting\');\r\necho $binding();\r\n//PHP 7 style\r\necho $getGreetingCallback-&gt;call(new Greeting);[/php]\r\n\r\n<h2>5. Null Coalesce(??) Operator</h2>\r\nThe null coalesce operator is an alternative for isset() function. This can be used for inline comparisons to check if a variable is set or not null. With this operator programmers get rid of ternary(?:) operator and code becomes more less.\r\n\r\n[php]$array = [\'greeting\'=&gt;\'Good Morning, Tricky Admin!\'];\r\n//PHP5 style\r\n$greet = isset($array[\'greeting\']) ? $array[\'greeting\'] : \'not set\';\r\necho $greet.PHP_EOL;\r\n//PHP7 style\r\n$greet = $array[\'greeting\'] ?? \'not set\';\r\necho $greet;[/php]\r\n\r\n<h2>6. Spaceship(&lt;=&gt;) Operator</h2>\r\nThis operator is used to compare two values inline. Instead of return true/false, it returns 0, -1, 1 when first variable is respectively equal, less than, or greater than second variable. The following code will make it more clear.\r\n\r\n[php]\r\n\r\n// 0 when both values are equal\r\n// -1 when the left value is less than the right value\r\n// 1 if the left value is greater than the right value\r\n\r\necho 1 &lt;=&gt; 1; // 0\r\necho 1 &lt;=&gt; 2; // -1\r\necho 2 &lt;=&gt; 1; // 1\r\n\r\n[/php]\r\n\r\n<h2>Performance</h2>\r\nIts worth to mention here that, PHP 7 is more faster than PHP older versions. Some programmers say that it is two times faster then PHP 5. We are very confident that it perform great and we are curious to see the average numbers once people start using it.\r\n\r\nThanks!', 'PHP 7 Features & Improvements', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'php-7-features-improvements', '', '', '2017-01-14 10:49:39', '2017-01-14 05:19:39', '', 0, 'http://trickntip.com/?p=249', 0, 'post', '', 0),
