(265, 1, '2017-01-17 17:56:44', '2017-01-17 12:26:44', 'Any program of any worth that you create has to work with data. Sometimes, the data is simple and straightforward — easy to work with. Other times, the data you have to work with is complex in its structure and meaning, forcing you to work hard to make sense of it all. You can use Python Lists to arrange your data: there\'s the list of books, your friend\'s list, and your to-do list etc. Arranging data in Python lists is so common that Python makes it easy for you to create and process lists in code.\r\n<h2>What are Python lists?</h2>\r\nPython lists are like arrays. When you create a list in Python, interpreter creates an array-like data structure in memory to save your data at runtime. Python lists use stack data structure. Like other programming languages, list indexes start form 0, the second index is 1 and so on. Lets see how to create a list:\r\n\r\n[python]students = [\'Scot\', &quot;Doe&quot;, \'John\', \'Amy\'][/python]\r\n\r\n[caption id=\"attachment_268\" align=\"alignnone\" width=\"211\"]<img class=\"size-full wp-image-268\" src=\"http://trickntip.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/01/Python-Lists-Stack.jpeg\" alt=\"Python Lists Stack Representation\" width=\"211\" height=\"137\" /> Python Lists Stack Representation[/caption]\r\n<h2>Access list data</h2>\r\nYou can access list\'s data using the standard square bracket offset notation.\r\n\r\n[python]print(students[1])[/python]\r\n\r\nDon\'t get surprised, the above statement will print the second name in the list i.e, Doe\r\n<h2>High level collection</h2>\r\nPython lists are high level collection means it can hold mixed data type values in the same list. Its not important that all list items should be of same data type. You can have string, number, float data types in the same list. Lets suppose we have to store student\'s name and age both in the same list.\r\n\r\n[python]students = [\'Scot\', 23, &quot;Doe&quot;, 25, \'John\', 24, \'Amy\', 20][/python]\r\n\r\nPython happily accepts this without any error or warning.\r\n<h2>Access list values</h2>\r\nList items can be access in several ways. Here, we assume that you know the indexes.\r\n\r\n[python]students = [\'Scot\', 23, &quot;Doe&quot;, 25, \'John\', 24, \'Amy\', 20]\r\nprint(students[0:2])[/python]\r\n\r\nThe above will produce the following output:\r\n<pre>[\'Scot\', 23]\r\n</pre>\r\nYes, you can pass the range with colon(:) inside square brackets where first number represents list index and second number represents the number of elements to be accessed. If second number is not specified, entire list will be accessed. Please see another example\r\n\r\n[python]students = [\'Scot\', 23, &quot;Doe&quot;, 25, \'John\', 24, \'Amy\', 20]\r\nprint(students[2:])[/python]\r\n\r\nInterpret the above code, you will see this output:\r\n<pre>[\'Doe\', 25, \'John\', 24, \'Amy\', 20]\r\n</pre>\r\n<h2>Update list values</h2>\r\nAs we have seen that we can access the list items/values using the list index, the same method can be use to update or overwrite the list values. Please see the following different example:\r\n\r\n[python]  \r\nmovies = [\'Titanic\', \'London Has Fallen\', \'Godzella\', \'Mission Impossible\']\r\n[/python]\r\n\r\nYou must notice that there is a spelling mistake in third movie name. Lets make it correct.\r\n\r\n[python]\r\nmovies[2] = \'Godzilla\'\r\n[/python]\r\n\r\n<h2>Summary</h2>\r\nAbove is the simple introduction of Python Lists that how you can create, access and update list values/items. Still there is much stuff that is left, like list methods the are Build-in Functions(BIFs) Python provides to perform operations easily.', 'Python Lists', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'python-lists', '', '', '2017-01-17 20:31:57', '2017-01-17 15:01:57', '', 0, 'http://trickntip.com/?p=265', 0, 'post', '', 1),
