error or warning.\r\n<h2>Access list values</h2>\r\nList items can be access in several ways. Here, we assume that you know the indexes.\r\n<pre>students = [\'Scot\', 23, \"Doe\", 25, \'John\', 24, \'Amy\', 20]\r\nprint(students[0:2])\r\n</pre>\r\nThe above will produce the following output:\r\n<pre>[\'Scot\', 23]\r\n</pre>\r\nYes, you can pass the range with colon(:) inside square brackets where first number represents list index and second number represents the number of elements to be accessed. If second number is not specified, entire list will be accessed. Please see another example\r\n<pre>students = [\'Scot\', 23, \"Doe\", 25, \'John\', 24, \'Amy\', 20]\r\nprint(students[2:])\r\n</pre>\r\nInterpret the above code, you will see this output:\r\n<pre>[\'Doe\', 25, \'John\', 24, \'Amy\', 20]\r\n</pre>\r\n<h2>Update list values</h2>\r\nAs we have seen that we can access the list items/values using the list index, the same method can be use to update or overwrite the list values. Please see the following different example:\r\n<pre>  \r\nmovies = [\'Titanic\', \'London Has Fallen\', \'Godzella\', \'Mission Impossible\']\r\n</pre>\r\nYou must notice that there is a spelling mistake in third movie name. Lets make it correct.\r\n<pre>movies[2] = \'Godzilla\'\r\n</pre>\r\n<h2>Summary</h2>\r\nAbove is the simple introduction of Python Lists that how you can create, access and update list values/items. Still there is much stuff that is left, like list methods the are Build-in Functions(BIFs) Python provides to perform operations easily.', 'Python Lists', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '265-revision-v1', '', '', '2017-01-17 17:56:44', '2017-01-17 12:26:44', '', 265, 'http://trickntip.com/265-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
