d movies.pop(-1) but if you write movies.pop(2), it will delete 3 element from the list.\r\n<h3>3. extend()</h3>\r\nIf you want to add a collection of data items in your existing list then you can use extend() function.\r\n<pre>movies = [\'Titanic\', \'London Has Fallen\', \'Godzilla\', \'Mission Impossible\']	\r\nmovies.extend([\'Wrong Turn 1\',\'Wrong Turn 2\'])\r\nprint(movies)\r\n</pre>\r\nResult:\r\n<pre>	[\'Titanic\', \'London Has Fallen\', \'Godzilla\', \'Mission Impossible\', \'Wrong Turn 1\', \'Wrong Turn 2\']\r\n</pre>\r\n<h3>4. insert()</h3>\r\ninsert() function is very much similar to append() function it takes two arguments, index and object. As name depicts that it inserts the object at a specific index location.\r\n<pre>movies = [\'Titanic\', \'London Has Fallen\', \'Godzilla\', \'Wrong Turn 2\', \'Mission Impossible\']	\r\nmovies.insert(3,\'Wrong Turn 1\')\r\nprint(movies)\r\n</pre>\r\nResult:\r\n<pre>	[\'Titanic\', \'London Has Fallen\', \'Godzilla\', \'Wrong Turn 1\', \'Wrong Turn 2\', \'Mission Impossible\']\r\n</pre>\r\n<h3>5. remove()</h3>\r\nThis method first find and remove a specific data item from your list. If data item not found then it will display \'ValueError: list.remove(x): x not in list\'.\r\n<pre>movies = [\'Titanic\', \'London Has Fallen\', \'Godzilla\', \'Mission Impossible\',\'Godzilla\']	\r\nmovies.remove(\'Godzilla\')\r\nprint(movies)\r\n</pre>\r\nResult:\r\n<pre>[\'Titanic\', \'London Has Fallen\', \'Mission Impossible\', \'Godzilla\']\r\n</pre>\r\n<b>Important:</b>One thing to note here that remove() function only removes the first occurence of data itme. From above list, it has only removed first \'Godzilla\' but not all.\r\n<h3>6. sort()</h3>\r\nAs a name depicts that it sorts the list in ascending order. It does not take any argument.\r\n<pre>movies = [\'Titanic\', \'London Has Fallen\', \'Wrong Turn 1\', \'Mission Impossible\',\'Godzilla\', \'Wrong Turn 2\', 2012]	\r\nmovies.sort()\r\nprint(movies)\r\n</pre>\r\nResult:\r\n<pre>[2012, \'Godzilla\', \'London Has Fallen\', \'Mission Impossible\', \'Titanic\', \'Wrong Turn 1\', \'Wrong Turn 2\']\r\n</pre>\r\n<h3>7. reverse()</h3>\r\nThe method reverse(), just change the order of data items of list in place. Like sort() function, it does not take any argument.\r\n<pre>movies = [\'Titanic\', \'London Has Fallen\', \'Wrong Turn 1\', \'Mission Impossible\',\'Godzilla\', \'Wrong Turn 2\']	\r\nmovies.reverse()\r\nprint(movies)\r\n</pre>\r\nResult:\r\n<pre>[\'Wrong Turn 2\', \'Godzilla\', \'Mission Impossible\', \'Wrong Turn 1\', \'London Has Fallen\', \'Titanic\']\r\n</pre>\r\n<h3>8. index()</h3>\r\nThis work in the same way as remove() does. But instead of remove the data item it returns the index of data item given as an argument. We will take the same example as we have taken for the remove() function before.\r\n<pre>movies = [\'Titanic\', \'London Has Fallen\', \'Godzilla\', \'Mission Impossible\',\'Godzilla\']	\r\nprint(movies.index(\'Godzilla\'))\r\n</pre>\r\nResult:\r\n<pre>2\r\n</pre>\r\n<b>Important:</b>It the item is not found in the list, it will give the ValueError.\r\n<h3>9. count()</h3>\r\ncount() method just counts the occurence of database item in the list. It takes exactly one argument.\r\n<pre>movies = [\'Titanic\', \'London Has Fallen\', \'Godzilla\', \'Mission Impossible\',\'Godzilla\']	\r\nprint(movies.count(\'Godzilla\'))\r\n</pre>\r\nResult:\r\n<pre>2\r\n</pre>\r\n<h2>Summary</h2>\r\nWe have given plenty of time for this article so that audience can understand Python List Methods in such an easy way. You can use IDLE(Integrated DeveLopement Environment) to run all these examples and explore more about these BIFs. We hope this post will definitly make your day.\r\n\r\nThanks!!', 'Python List Methods', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '274-revision-v1', '', '', '2017-01-18 16:54:35', '2017-01-18 11:24:35', '', 274, 'http://trickntip.com/274-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
