(368, 1, '2017-11-24 12:55:50', '2017-11-24 07:25:50', '<p>Python is a great language for doing data analysis beacause of its available packages. Pandas is an open-source, BSD-licensed <b>Python</b> library providing easy-to-use data structures, high-performance and data analysis tools for the Python programming language. Pandas makes importing and analyzing data much easier. Pandas builds on packages like <b><a href=\"http://www.numpy.org/\">NumPy</a></b> and <b> <a href =\"https://matplotlib.org/\">matplotlib</a></b> to give you a single, convenient, place to do most of your data analysis and visualization work.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>One of the most powerful aspects of Pandas is it\'s easy inclusion into the Matplotlib module. Matplotlib is a popular and robust Python module that allows programmers to create graphs and charts from their data. Pandas makes loading your data into Matplotlib slightly easier, as well as handles almost all of the processing necessary to get it ready for Matplotlib. Pandas is basically created to do this in the most efficient way possible.</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Basic Plotting</li>\r\n	<li>Bar Plot</li>\r\n	<li>Histograms</li>\r\n	<li>Box Plots</li>\r\n	<li>Area Plot</li>\r\n	<li>Scatter Plot</li>\r\n	<li>Pie Chart</li>\r\n	<li>Box Plots</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<h3>Basic Plotting</h3>\r\n<p> For basic plotting, we have used the numpy library for generating the random data. </p>\r\n\r\n[python] \r\n	import matplotlib.pyplot as plt \r\n	import pandas as pd\r\n	import numpy as np\r\n	df = pd.DataFrame(np.random.randn(10,4),index=pd.date_range(\'1/1/2000\', periods=10), columns=list(\'ABCD\'))\r\n	df.plot()\r\n	show.plot()\r\n[/python] \r\n\r\n<p>Its <b>output</b> is as follows </p>\r\n<img src=\"http://trickntip.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/11/basic-plot.png\" alt=\"basic-plot\" width=\"714\" height=\"513\" class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-369\" />\r\n\r\n<h3>Bar Plot (Vertical)</h3>\r\n<p>A vertical bar plot can be created in the following way </p>\r\n[python] \r\n	import matplotlib.pyplot as plt \r\n	import pandas as pd\r\n	import numpy as np\r\n	df = pd.DataFrame(np.random.randn(10,4),index=pd.date_range(\'1/1/2000\', periods=10), columns=list(\'ABCD\'))\r\n	df.plot.bar()\r\n	show.plot()\r\n[/python] \r\n<p>Its <b>output</b> is as follows </p>\r\n<img src=\"http://trickntip.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/11/bar-plot.png\" alt=\"bar-plot\" width=\"648\" height=\"515\" class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-370\" />\r\n<p>To produce a stacked bar plot, pass stacked=True in the plot method like</p>\r\n[python] \r\n	import matplotlib.pyplot as plt\r\n	import pandas as pd\r\n	import numpy as np\r\n	df = pd.DataFrame(np.random.randn(10,4),index=pd.date_range(\'1/1/2000\', periods=10), columns=list(\'ABCD\'))	\r\n	df.plot.bar(stacked=True)\r\n	show.plot()\r\n[/python] \r\n<img src=\"http://trickntip.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/11/bar-plot-stacked.png\" alt=\"bar-plot-stacked\" width=\"652\" height=\"526\" class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-371\" />\r\n\r\n<h3>Bar Plot (horizontal)</h3>\r\n<p>To get horizontal bar plots, use the barh() method </p>\r\n[python] \r\n	import matplotlib.pyplot as plt \r\n	import pandas as pd\r\n	import numpy as np\r\n	df = pd.DataFrame(np.random.randn(10,4),index=pd.date_range(\'1/1/2000\', periods=10), columns=list(\'ABCD\'))\r\n	df.plot.barh()\r\n	show.plot()\r\n[/python] \r\n<p>Its <b>output</b> is as follows </p>\r\n<img src=\"http://trickntip.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/11/bar-plot-horizontal.png\" alt=\"bar-plot-horizontal\" width=\"651\" height=\"520\" class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-372\" />\r\n\r\n<p>To produce a stacked bar plot, pass stacked=True in the plot method like</p>\r\n[python] \r\n	import matplotlib.pyplot as plt \r\n	import pandas as pd\r\n	import numpy as np\r\n	df = pd.DataFrame(np.random.randn(10,4),index=pd.date_range(\'24/11/2017\', periods=10), columns=list(\'ABCD\'))\r\n	df.plot.barh(stacked=True)\r\n	show.plot()\r\n[/python] \r\n<img src=\"http://trickntip.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/11/bar-plot-horizontal-stacked.png\" alt=\"bar-plot-horizontal-stacked\" width=\"649\" height=\"516\" class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-373\" />\r\n\r\n<h3>Histograms</h3>\r\n<p>The plot.hist() method is used to plot the Histograms.</p>\r\n[python] \r\n	import matplotlib.pyplot as plt \r\n	import pandas as pd\r\n	import numpy as np\r\n	df = pd.DataFrame(np.random.randn(10,4),index=pd.date_range(\'1/1/2000\', periods=10), columns=list(\'ABCD\'))\r\n	df.plot.hist(bins=20)\r\n	show.plot()\r\n[/python] \r\n<img src=\"http://trickntip.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/11/histogram-plot.png\" alt=\"histogram-plot\" width=\"648\" height=\"547\" class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-374\" />\r\n\r\n<h3>Box Plots</h3>\r\n[python] \r\n	import matplotlib.pyplot as plt\r\n	import pandas as pd\r\n	import numpy as np\r\n	df = pd.DataFrame(np.random.rand(10, 6), columns=[\'A\', \'B\', \'C\', \'D\',\'E\',\'F\'])\r\n	df.plot.box()\r\n	show.plot()\r\n[/python] \r\n<img src=\"http://trickntip.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/11/box-plot.png\" alt=\"box-plot\" width=\"652\" height=\"556\" class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-375\" />\r\n\r\n<h3>Area Plot</h3>\r\n\r\n[python]\r\n	import matplotlib.pyplot as plt \r\n	import pandas as pd\r\n	import numpy as np\r\n	df = pd.DataFrame(np.random.rand(10, 6), columns=[\'A\', \'B\', \'C\', \'D\',\'E\',\'F\'])\r\n	df.plot.area()\r\n	show.plot()\r\n[/python]\r\n<img src=\"http://trickntip.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/11/area-plot.png\" alt=\"area-plot\" width=\"648\" height=\"552\" class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-376\" />\r\n\r\n<h3>Scatter Plot</h3>\r\n[python]\r\n	import matplotlib.pyplot as plt\r\n	import pandas as pd\r\n	import numpy as np\r\n	df = pd.DataFrame(np.random.rand(50, 4), columns=[\'a\', \'b\', \'c\', \'d\'])\r\n	df.plot.scatter(x=\'a\', y=\'b\')\r\n	show.plot()\r\n[/python]\r\n<p></p>\r\n<img src=\"http://trickntip.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/11/scater-plot.png\" alt=\"scater-plot\" width=\"648\" height=\"544\" class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-377\" />\r\n\r\n<h3>Pie Plot</h3>\r\n[python]\r\n	import matplotlib.pyplot as plt\r\n	import pandas as pd\r\n	import numpy as np\r\n	df = pd.DataFrame(np.random.rand(6), index=[\'a\', \'b\', \'c\', \'d\',\'e\',\'f\'])\r\n	df.plot.pie(subplots=True)\r\n	show.plot()\r\n[/python]\r\n<img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-359\" src=\"pie-plot.png\" alt=\"trickntip.com googleapps\" width=\"400\" height=\"400\" style=\"padding-left: 5%\" />\r\n\r\n\r\n<h2>Summary</h2>\r\n<p>I hope this is useful. Feel free to provide feedback in the comments and let me know if this is helpful. Thanks!</p>\r\n', 'Visualize data with Pandas', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'visualize-data-pandas', '', '', '2017-11-24 12:55:50', '2017-11-24 07:25:50', '', 0, 'http://trickntip.com/?p=368', 0, 'post', '', 0),
