(387, 1, '2017-11-29 12:54:22', '2017-11-29 07:24:22', 'In this article I will cover *args and **kwargs in Python. If you\'re new to python or Django you may have seen them all over the place. Several beginners confused with C(Programming Language) pointers, but * and ** are totally different from the C pointers. Asterisk and double asterisk are used in the function definition. Let\'s dive in and have a look on asterisk* and double asterisk** in Python.\r\n\r\nBefore we start, let\'s understand function with the very simple example.\r\n\r\n[python]\r\n# function definition\r\ndef greeting():\r\n    print(\'Good morning!!!\')\r\n\r\n\r\n# function calling\r\ngreeting()\r\n[/python]\r\n\r\nI know this is very simple stuff. You might already know this but it is worth to explain here that what is function and how to call a function in Python. Here, greeting(): is the name of the function and it\'s simply called with the name greeting() where needed.\r\n<h2>What are arguments?</h2>\r\nA function can accept values and these values can be of any data type like string, object, integer etc. Arguments are used to pass these values to a function. Let us modify the greeting() function so that it can accept the values to print a name of the person along with greeting.\r\n\r\n[python]\r\n# function definition\r\ndef greeting(name):\r\n    print(\'Good morning,\', name)\r\n\r\n\r\n# function calling\r\ngreeting(\'Jack\')\r\n[/python]\r\n\r\nThe value \'Jack\' is passed from function calling as a parameter and it will be copied to name argument in the function definition. Now, <code>name</code> can be used anywhere in the function definition as a regular variable.\r\n<h2>What are keyword arguments?</h2>\r\nPython has a great feature of keyword arguments where other languages like C, C++ etc do not have this feature. Once again, let\'s modify our greeting function so that it can accept keyword arguments.\r\n\r\n[python]\r\n# function definition\r\ndef greeting(name=\'world\', time=\'9:00 AM\'):\r\n    print(\'Good morning,\', name)\r\n    print(&quot;It\'s&quot;, time)\r\n[/python]\r\n\r\nNow our function is ready to accept keyword arguments. Let\'s call this function in different ways and notice the behavior.\r\n\r\n[python]\r\n# function calling without any argument\r\ngreeting()\r\n# Good morning, world\r\n# It\'s 9:00 AM\r\n\r\n# function calling with only one argument\r\ngreeting(\'Jack\')\r\n# Good morning, Jack\r\n# It\'s 9:00 AM\r\n\r\n# function calling with all arguments\r\ngreeting(\'Jack\', \'7:30 AM\')\r\n# Good morning, Jack\r\n# It\'s 7:30 AM\r\n[/python]\r\n\r\nYou may be noticed that if the argument is not given to the function then it holds its default value that is assigned in a function definition. Now if you only want to pass the time to greeting() function then how will you do this. This is the case when keyword arguments are used and makes Python different than other languages.\r\n\r\n[python]\r\n# function calling with keyword arguments\r\ngreeting(time=\'7:30 AM\')\r\n# Good morning, world\r\n# It\'s 7:30 AM\r\n\r\n# function calling with changing the position of keyword arguments\r\ngreeting(time=\'7:30 AM\', name=\'John\')\r\n# Good morning, John\r\n# It\'s 7:30 AM\r\n[/python]\r\n\r\nAwesome! now we are good to go with our actual topic of this article that is asterisk and double asterisk. Please see the following example to calculate the sum of three numbers:\r\n<h2>Use of *args</h2>\r\n\r\n[python]\r\n# function definition\r\ndef calculate_sum(a, b, c):\r\n    &quot;&quot;&quot;This function is used calculate the sum of three numbers&quot;&quot;&quot;\r\n    return a + b + c\r\n[/python]\r\n\r\n<code>calculate_sum</code> function looks similar to <code>greeting</code> function above. Let\'s modifiy this function to understand the use of * in function definition. I promise, you will definitly like this:\r\n\r\n[python]\r\n# function definition\r\ndef calculate_sum(*args):\r\n    &quot;&quot;&quot;This function is used calculate the sum of three numbers&quot;&quot;&quot;\r\n    print(type(args))  # &lt;class \'tuple\'&gt;\r\n    s = 0\r\n    for number in args:\r\n        s += number\r\n    return s\r\n\r\n\r\n# function calling\r\nprint(\'Sum:\', calculate_sum(1, 2, 4)) \r\n[/python]\r\n\r\nOutput:\r\n<pre>&lt;class \'tuple\'&gt;\r\nSum: 7\r\n</pre>\r\nThe arguments given in the function calling will be packed into tupple data type implicitly. Now if you want to calculate the sum of more numbers then you can call this function like:\r\n\r\n[python]\r\n# function calling\r\nprint(\'Sum:\', calculate_sum(1, 2, 4, 5, 6, 7, 8, 9))\r\n[/python]\r\n\r\n\r\n<h2>Use of **kwargs</h2>\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nWhere *args is used to store arguments, **kwargs is used to store keyword arguments. Let\'s see the following simple example of ** in function definition:\r\n\r\n[python]\r\n# function definition\r\ndef print_kwargs(**kwargs):\r\n    print(type(kwargs))\r\n    for name, value in kwargs.items():\r\n        print(\'{} =&gt; {}\'.format(name, value))\r\n\r\n\r\n# function calling\r\nprint_kwargs(dog=\'pet\', apple=\'fruit\', name=\'Jack Denial\', fish=\'pet\')\r\n[/python]\r\n\r\nOutput:\r\n<pre>&lt;class \'dict\'&gt;\r\ndog =&gt; pet\r\nname =&gt; Jack Denial\r\napple =&gt; fruit\r\nfish =&gt; pet\r\n</pre>\r\nThe arguments given in the function calling will be packed into dict data type implicitly and you can access this using the for loop.\r\n<h2>Summary</h2>\r\nNext time, you do not need to confuse when you see * and ** in Django or any other Python framework. I am very much eager to write more posts on * and ** topic where you can see we can use both in the same function. Even you guys can explore more about this. These kinds of concepts are also used in decorators. If you have any question please leave that in the comments below. Thanks!', 'asterisk* and double asterisk** in Python', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '381-revision-v1', '', '', '2017-11-29 12:54:22', '2017-11-29 07:24:22', '', 381, 'http://trickntip.com/381-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0);
