(393, 1, '2017-12-04 14:17:48', '2017-12-04 08:47:48', 'In this article, I am going over Generators that why you want to use them and some of the advantages they have over lists. There are many tasks that use much memory, then we can use Generators there. Generators return an iterable set of items, one at a time, in a special way. Its often said that Generators are easy to implement but bit difficult to understand. Actually, it\'s really not true. Just open your python editor and implement few code examples with me.\n\nBefore we start implementing, let\'s write a simple program to calculate the square of all numbers present in the list and return a list:\n\n[python]\ndef cal_square(numbers):\n    &quot;&quot;&quot;This function is used to calculate the square of given list numbers&quot;&quot;&quot;\n    result = []\n    for n in numbers:\n        result.append(n * n)\n    return result\n\n\nresult = cal_square([1, 2, 3, 4, 5])\nprint(result)\n[/python]\n\nOutput:\n<pre>[1, 4, 9, 16, 25]\n</pre>\nNow let\'s do this using generator:\n\n[python]\ndef cal_square(numbers):\n    &quot;&quot;&quot;This function is used to calculate the square of given list numbers&quot;&quot;&quot;\n    for n in numbers:\n        yield n * n\n\n\nresult = cal_square([1, 2, 3, 4, 5])\nprint(result)\n[/python]\n\nOutput:\n<pre> &lt;generator object cal_square at 0x7f564003f0d8&gt;</pre>\nA <code>yield</code> keyword what makes it a generator, is used. If you notice the output, <code>cal_square</code> is a generator object here. The reason for this is because generators do not hold entire result in memory it yields one result at a time. So really it is waiting for us to ask for the first result and did not compute anything yet.\n\n[python]\nprint(next(result)) # gives 1\n[/python]\n\nNow when <code>result</code> is passed in <code>next()</code> function, we yield it out 1 times and result is 1. Let\'s call <code>next()</code> function few times more.\n\n[python]\nprint(next(result)) # gives 1 \nprint(next(result)) # gives 4\nprint(next(result)) # gives 9\nprint(next(result)) # gives 16\nprint(next(result)) # gives 25\n[/python]\n\nYou see each time I run <code>next()</code>, it executes generator and get the next value. 25 is the last value from our result here. lets run <code>next()</code> one more time.\n\n[python]\nprint(next(result)) # gives 25\n[/python]\n\nOutput:\n<pre>Traceback (most recent call last):\n  File \"/var/www/html/python-programs/generators.py\", line 27, in \n    print(next(result))\nStopIteration\n</pre>\nI got an error here and the exception \'StopIteration\' that means entire generator has been exhausted and stop iteration means it\'s out of values. Now instead of getting these values one at time. Lets do this using a for loop:\n\n[python]\nfor num in result:\n    print(num)\n[/python]\n\nOutput:\n<pre>1\n4\n9\n16\n25\n</pre>\nWe get all the values and did not get stop iteration exception because for loop knows where to stop the iterations.\n\n<code>yield</code> is one way to create generators but there is one another way to create generators. To understand this lets do the same thing using list comprehensions:\n\n[python]\nresult = [n * n for n in [1, 2, 3, 4, 5]]\nprint(result)\n[/python]\n\nOutput:\n<pre>[1, 4, 9, 16, 25]\n</pre>\nNow you can create a generator in the same way, just need to use the parenthesis and remove brackets.\n\n[python]\nresult = (n * n for n in [1, 2, 3, 4, 5])\nprint(result)\n[/python]\n\nOutput:\n<pre> at 0x7fa693d0e120&gt;\n</pre>\nYou can iterate you <code>result</code> object and get the squares of your list. Even you can convert a generator into a list:\n\n[python]\nprint(list(result))\n[/python]\n\nOutput:\n<pre>[1, 4, 9, 16, 25]\n</pre>\n<h3 class=\"text-success\">Advantages of Generators</h3>\n1. More readable code when using <code>yield</code> keyword instead of <code>return</code> the result.\n2. Generators are better with the performance\n<h2>How generators are better with the performance?</h2>\nYou might note in the above examples that generator expression or function is only executed when we call <code>next()</code> function or when we loop over it. That means our memory is free because it does not hold any result values. Let\'s see few more following examples which can even halt your system processes:\n\n[python]\nimport time\n\nstart = time.time()\nnums = (n * n for n in range(9000000))\nprint(\'Generator took\', (time.time() - start) * 1000, \'milliseconds\')\n\nstart = time.time()\nnums = [n * n for n in range(9000000)]\nprint(\'List took\', (time.time() - start) * 1000, \'milliseconds\')\n[/python]\n\nOutput:\n<pre>Generator took 0.010251998901367188 milliseconds\nList took 854.7539710998535 milliseconds\n</pre>\nNotice the time taken by list and generator. You can see that list is taking much time as compare to generator.\n<h2>Summary</h2>\nYou need to make a decision that where you can use a generator and where you can use list. You can do more exercises with generators and explore the things. If you have any question please leave that in the comments below. Thanks!', 'Generators', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '390-autosave-v1', '', '', '2017-12-04 14:17:48', '2017-12-04 08:47:48', '', 390, 'http://trickntip.com/390-autosave-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
