(399, 1, '2017-12-05 11:10:29', '2017-12-05 05:40:29', 'A programming language is said to have <b>first-class function</b> if it treats function as <b>first-class citizen</b>. Now, what is a first-class citizen? In programming language design, a first-class citizen (also type, object, entity, or value) in a given programming language is an entity which supports all the operations generally available to other entities. These operations typically include being passed as an argument, returned from a function, modified, and assigned to a variable. A first-class citizen is also known as first-class object.\r\n\r\nFrom the above definition, it is clear that a language is having first class citizen if a function is:\r\n1. Assigned to a variable and treated as same entity\r\n2. Pass function as an argument to other function\r\n3. A function can return a function\r\n\r\nAll functions in Python are first-class functions. They are not a special kind of function but you can assign any function to a variable and use that variable to call that function. Enough with the introductory part. Let\'s see few code examples:\r\n<h2>Assign function to a variable</h2>\r\nLets create a function to calculate a square and return the calculated value.\r\n\r\n[python]\r\ndef square(n):\r\n    return n * n\r\n\r\n\r\ns = square(4)  # assign return value to a variable\r\nfunc = square  # assign function to a variable\r\nprint(s)\r\nprint(func)\r\nprint(func(6))\r\n[/python]\r\n\r\nOutput:\r\n<pre>16\r\n&lt;function square at 0x7fa6f0a66b70&gt;\r\n36	\r\n</pre>\r\nWhen we use parenthesis, that means we are executing the function like <code>s = square(4)</code> and storing the result into <code>s</code> variable. The statment <code>func = square</code> is what, we are assigning a function into <code>func</code> variable and <code>func</code> can be used to call <code>square</code> function.\r\n<h2>Pass function as an argument to a function</h2>\r\nSo far, we have assigned a function to a variable and use that variable to call the function but we can pass a function as an argument to a function. <b>If a function accepts other functions as an argument or returns functions as their result that\'s what you call a higher-order function</b>. Lets look at the example to passing a function to other function as an argument.\r\n\r\n[python]\r\ndef square(n):\r\n    &quot;&quot;&quot;Calculate the square of a number&quot;&quot;&quot;\r\n    return n * n\r\n\r\n\r\ndef cube(n):\r\n    &quot;&quot;&quot;Calculate the cube of a number&quot;&quot;&quot;\r\n    return n * n * n\r\n\r\n\r\ndef my_map_func(func, numbers_list):\r\n    &quot;&quot;&quot;This function will behave like a built-in map function&quot;&quot;&quot;\r\n    result = []\r\n    for n in numbers_list:\r\n        result.append(func(n))\r\n    return result\r\n\r\n\r\nresult = my_map_func(cube, [2, 3, 4, 5, 6])\r\nprint(result)\r\n[/python]\r\n\r\nOutput:\r\n<pre>[8, 27, 64, 125, 216]\r\n</pre>\r\nI have created <code>my_map_func</code> from scratch that will behave similar like built-in map function. There are two other functions <code>square</code> and <code>cube</code>. If you see, I have passed <code>cube</code> function as an argument to <code>my_map_function</code>, now <code>my_map_function</code> will return the list of calculated cube values. If you want to calculate the square of this list then you can pass <code>square</code> function as parameter to <code>my_map_func</code> like:\r\n\r\n[python]\r\nresult = my_map_func(square, [2, 3, 4, 5, 6])\r\nprint(result)\r\n[/python]\r\n\r\nOutput:\r\n<pre>[4, 9, 16, 25, 36]\r\n</pre>\r\nNow you can pass any function to our custom <code>my_map_func</code> function.\r\n<h2>A function can return a function</h2>\r\nLets look like at return a function from another function with very simple example:\r\n\r\n[python]\r\ndef html_tag(tag):\r\n    def wrap_text(text):\r\n        print(\'&lt;{0}&gt;{1}&lt;/{0}&gt;\'.format(tag, text))\r\n\r\n    return wrap_text\r\n\r\n\r\nheading1 = html_tag(\'h1\')\r\nheading1(\'This is heading 1\')\r\n[/python]\r\n\r\nOutput:\r\n<pre>&lt;h1&gt;This is heading 1&lt;/h1&gt;\r\n</pre>\r\nWe have set <code>heading1</code> equal to <code>html_tag</code> function and <code>html_tag</code> returns <code>wrap_text</code> function. Now <code>heading1</code> variable can be used to call <code>wrap_text</code> function. The most important thing is that, the value passed in <code>html_tag(\'h1\')</code> will also be recorded in <code>heading1</code> variable and will be concatinated when <code>heading1</code> will be called.\r\n\r\nNow if you want to make a paragraph then you can do simply the following:\r\n\r\n[python]\r\nparagraph = html_tag(\'p\')\r\nparagraph(\'This is long paragraph\')\r\n[/python]\r\n\r\nOutput:\r\n<pre>&lt;p&gt;This is long paragraph&lt;/p&gt;</pre>\r\n<h2>Summary</h2>\r\nJavascript also has first-class function. You guys can try the same examples in Javascript with the javascript syntax. If you have any question please leave that in the comments below. Thanks!', 'First-Class Functions in Python', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'first-class-functions-python', '', '', '2017-12-05 11:13:59', '2017-12-05 05:43:59', '', 0, 'http://trickntip.com/?p=399', 0, 'post', '', 0),
